t","Drains to superior mesenteric nodes","Drains to para-aortic nodes then thoracic duct","Drains to coeliac nodes then cisterna chyli"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe jejunum, like other midgut structures, \u003Cstrong\u003Edrains to superior mesenteric nodes \u003C/strong\u003Eand then on to the cisterna chyli. Lymphatic vessels follow the arterial supply, with lymph nodes arranged in groups along the superior mesenteric vessels before ultimately draining via the intestinal trunk into the cisterna chyli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains to inferior mesenteric nodes\u003C/strong\u003E - These nodes receive drainage from hindgut structures\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains directly to thoracic duct\u003C/strong\u003E - Lymph must first pass through regional nodes before reaching the thoracic duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains to para-aortic nodes then thoracic duct\u003C/strong\u003E - While some lymph may pass through para-aortic nodes, the primary pathway is via superior mesenteric nodes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains to coeliac nodes then cisterna chyli\u003C/strong\u003E - Coeliac nodes receive drainage from foregut structures\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superior mesenteric lymph nodes receive lymphatic drainage from midgut structures between the ampulla of Vater and the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon.","Lymphatic vessels follow the arterial supply, with lymph nodes arranged in groups along the superior mesenteric vessels.","The superior mesenteric lymph nodes ultimately drain into the cisterna chyli via the intestinal trunk."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human 